title: [NO REVIEW REQUIRED] POC: Integrate DeepSpeed CUDA Transformer kernels into ORT
body:
**Description**:

This is a simple POC showing the integration of the `DeepSpeed` Transformer CUDA kernels (provided via a shared library) into ORT. 

The `DeepSpeed` component is designed to be a "bring your kernel registry" (optional) plugin in the CUDA EP that will have a kernel registry that co-exists with the "stock" CUDA EP kernel registry and a `SessionOption` knob is exposed so that a user can indicate if the `DeepSpeed` CUDA kernels are to be preferred ahead of the stock kernels while partitioning the model graph. 

To build a flavor of ORT that supports the `DeepSpeed` kernels, a build flag `--enable_deep_speed_cuda_kernels` is to be used along with regular CUDA build flags (only CUDA build flavor can support `DeepSpeed` kernels). Currently, this build flavor is only supported on Linux.

As a first step, the `DeepSpeed` kernel registry supports one simple kernel (`BiasGelu`) and a test is added for the same. This PR does not contain any API level changes. 

**Motivation and Context**
Use `DeepSpeed` via ORT

body:
**Describe the bug**
I exported torchvision's mask-RCNN as an ONNX model and used `onnxruntime-gpu` to run inference with it. This works fine for a single image. Running a list of images, one at a time, through the same onnxruntime session works fine using the CPU execution provider. When using the CUDA execution provider, however, I get a CUDNN error if the first image has zero detections and the next image has at least some detections.

**Urgency**
I can work around this for now by re-instantiating the onnxruntime session as necessary, but it's not a preferred solution.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Linux Ubuntu 20.04
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): binary from PyPI
- ONNX Runtime version: onnxruntime-gpu 1.10.0
- Python version: 3.8
- CUDA/cuDNN version: CUDA version 11.4, cuDNN version 8.2.4.15-1 (installed using `apt install libcudnn8==8.2.4.15-1+cuda11.4`)
- GPU model and memory: Tried on NVIDIA GeForce 2070 Super 8GB and NVIDIA GeForce 950M 4GB

**To Reproduce**

Here's a minimum reproducible example:

```python
import torch
import torchvision
import numpy as np
import onnxruntime
from PIL import Image
import urllib

torch.manual_seed(0)

# download test image from COCO dataset
urllib.request.urlretrieve(
    "https://farm9.staticflickr.com/8289/7717265494_a6c6ac01bb_z.jpg",
    filename="test.jpg",
)

model = torchvision.models.detection.maskrcnn_resnet50_fpn(pretrained=True)
model.eval()

dummy_input = torch.rand(1, 3, 800, 800)

torch.onnx.export(
    model,
    dummy_input,
    "maskrcnn.onnx",
    opset_version=14,
    input_names=["input"],
    output_names=["boxes", "labels", "scores", "masks"],
    dynamic_axes={
        "input": [0, 1, 2, 3],
        "boxes": [0, 1],
        "labels": [0],
        "scores": [0],
        "masks": [0, 1, 2, 3],
    },
)

# load model
with open("maskrcnn.onnx", "rb") as f:
    sess = onnxruntime.InferenceSession(f.read(), providers=["CUDAExecutionProvider"])
input_name = sess.get_inputs()[0].name

# run inference on empty image
image = np.zeros(shape=(1, 3, 800, 800), dtype=np.float32)
pred = sess.run(None, {input_name: image})
boxes, labels, scores, masks = pred
print("Number of detections: ", len(boxes))

# run inference on test image
image = Image.open("test.jpg")
image = np.float32(image)
image = np.moveaxis(image, -1, 0)  # HWC to CHW
image = image[np.newaxis, :]  # add batch dimension

pred = sess.run(None, {input_name: image})
boxes, labels, scores, masks = pred
print("Number of detections: ", len(boxes))

```

**Expected behavior**

Number of detections:  3 (or some number greater than zero)

body:
**Description**: 

1. Solve some SDL warnings
2. Refactor Training GPU Windows CI pipeline job, to make similar to the inference one. And I need to disable the static analysis for now. Fixing the warnings will need more changes, which will make this PR even bigger. 
3. Add a customized SDL ruleset file, which is based on the VC++ default one with a few additional enabled warnings.  The list of warnings is picked up from https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/cpp/code-quality/code-analysis-for-cpp-corecheck?view=msvc-170 .  Some of the warnings enforce using unique_ptr/shared_ptr instead of raw pointer to meet our compliance requirement.

When this PR is checked in, if you have code like:
```c++
char *buffer = nullptr;
if (useCache)
    buffer = GetCache();
else
    buffer = new char[bufferSize];  // C26400
```

It will be rejected by static analyzer. Because 26400 is in our SDL.rules file. You may convert it to:

```c++
std::unique_ptr<char[]> buffer;
if (useCache)
    buffer = GetCache();
else
    buffer = std::make_unique<char[]>(bufferSize); 
```

We still have a lot C26451 warnings that  I couldn't get them fixed this time. So I disabled them to make the CI pass. Next, I will add "C26406 DONT_ASSIGN_RAW_TO_OWNER" to the warning list. 

To try the static analyzer locally,  please open CMakeLists.txt and uncomment the following lines:
```cmake
#if(WIN32 AND onnxruntime_ENABLE_STATIC_ANALYSIS)
  #  set_target_properties(${target_name} PROPERTIES VS_USER_PROPS ${PROJECT_SOURCE_DIR}/EnableVisualStudioCodeAnalysis.props)
#endif()
```
Then build it with "--extra_cmake_defines onnxruntime_ENABLE_STATIC_ANALYSIS=ON".
**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?

To meet compliance requirement and have better code quality.  For example, C26478 is one of the warnings we will enable through this PR.  And it helped me found a bug in conv_transpose_attributes.h

**Description**:

title: fix deadlock in model.train mode forward run only
body:
**Description**: fix deadlock in model.train model forward run only.

Issues identified and investigated by Aishwarya. 

When training program exits, PyNodeSharedPointerPool destructor is called, if grad_fns_ is not empty,
PyNode::release_variables() will be called (https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/blob/15532595209d2daf34d35e10f8d3d3b64966aea2/torch/csrc/autograd/python_function.cpp#L168)

The other hand, there is known issue when acquiring GIL in pybind11 destructors, there will be probabbly deadlock issue (https://github.com/pybind/pybind11/issues/1446)

The resolution here, we remove all maintained states before ~PyNodeSharedPointerPool happens (e.g. the python program exits) to avoid the deadlock issue.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

title: DirectML EP remove stale code for int64 emulated via int32 double strides
body:
**Description**: This deletes now stale code in the DML EP that simulated int64 tensor support via doubled strides with int32 (which was obviously problematic for cases that generated numbers greater than 4 billion, and mitigated by fallback to CPU in such uncertain cases). Now that DirectML 1.8 (adopted in PR https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/9765) supports int64 directly for all operators which previously used the doubled strides workaround, this code is moot.

**Motivation and Context**
- *Why is this change required?* It's not required, but it's good cleanup to reduce the complexity of the code for maintainers.

title: ORT Eager aten view operation needs to share the same semantic with Pytorch view
body:
**Feature request**
The implementation of the aten view operation [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/orttraining/orttraining/eager/ort_aten.cpp#L259
) is done by a reshaped copy which returns a tensor that lives in a memory location that is different from the underlying storage of the original tensor. Meanwhile, Pytorch [implementation ](https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/blob/834bd3134eab322151a769589f6fb47c6c888342/aten/src/ATen/native/TensorShape.cpp#L1034) return a view which share the same storage with the original tensor

**Proposal**
Modify the aten view implementation in ORT eager backend to match with Pytorch implementation to improve perf
